  "text": "# Apache Flink Windowing API Extension Points\n\n## Overview\nApache Flink's windowing API provides several key extension points that developers implement to create custom window assigners and triggers. The architecture follows a hierarchical design with abstract base classes and specialized subclasses for different windowing patterns.\n\n## 1. WindowAssigner - Core Extension Point\n**File:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/WindowAssigner.java`\n\nThe abstract base class `WindowAssigner<T, W extends Window>` defines the primary extension point. Developers must implement four abstract methods:\n\n- **`Collection<W> assignWindows(T element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)`** - Called for each incoming element to determine which windows it belongs to. Returns zero or more windows.\n- **`Trigger<T, W> getDefaultTrigger()`** - Provides the default trigger for this assigner. Determines when window results fire.\n- **`TypeSerializer<W> getWindowSerializer(ExecutionConfig executionConfig)`** - Returns a serializer for the window type for fault tolerance.\n- **`boolean isEventTime()`** - Indicates whether windows are assigned based on event time (true) or processing time (false).\n\nThe `WindowAssignerContext` inner abstract class provides access to `getCurrentProcessingTime()`, allowing assigners to query the current processing time during assignment.\n\n## 2. MergingWindowAssigner - For Session-Style Windows\n**File:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/MergingWindowAssigner.java`\n\nExtends `WindowAssigner<T, W>` to support merging of windows. Developers implementing session windows must extend this class and implement:\n\n- **`void mergeWindows(Collection<W> windows, MergeCallback<W> callback)`** - Determines which windows should be merged. Calls `callback.merge(toBeMerged, mergeResult)` for each group of windows that should merge.\n\nThe `MergeCallback<W>` interface has one method: `merge(Collection<W> toBeMerged, W mergeResult)` - invoked to signal which windows merge into a result window.\n\n## 3. Trigger - Lifecycle Control\n**File:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/triggers/Trigger.java`\n\nThe abstract base class `Trigger<T, W extends Window>` controls pane firing with four key lifecycle methods:\n\n- **`TriggerResult onElement(T element, long timestamp, W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** - Called when an element is added to a pane. Determines if the pane should fire.\n- **`TriggerResult onProcessingTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** - Called when a processing-time timer fires.\n- **`TriggerResult onEventTime(long time, W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** - Called when an event-time timer fires (when watermark passes registered time).\n- **`void clear(W window, TriggerContext ctx)`** - Called during window cleanup. Must delete all timers and state.\n\nOptional methods for merging support:\n\n- **`boolean canMerge()`** - Returns true if the trigger supports window merging (default: false).\n- **`void onMerge(W window, OnMergeContext ctx)`** - Called when windows merge. Must handle merging of trigger state if `canMerge()` returns true.\n\nThe `TriggerContext` interface provides state management and timer registration:\n- `registerEventTimeTimer(long time)`, `registerProcessingTimeTimer(long time)` - Register callbacks\n- `deleteEventTimeTimer(long time)`, `deleteProcessingTimeTimer(long time)` - Delete callbacks\n- `<S extends State> S getPartitionedState(StateDescriptor<S, ?> stateDescriptor)` - Access fault-tolerant state\n- `getCurrentWatermark()`, `getCurrentProcessingTime()` - Query current time\n\nThe `OnMergeContext` extends `TriggerContext` with `mergePartitionedState()` for merging state during window merge operations.\n\n## 4. EventTimeSessionWindows - Reference Implementation\n**File:** `flink-streaming-java/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/assigners/EventTimeSessionWindows.java`\n\nDemonstrates a concrete `MergingWindowAssigner<Object, TimeWindow>` implementation:\n\n- **`assignWindows(Object element, long timestamp, WindowAssignerContext context)`** - Creates a single `TimeWindow(timestamp, timestamp + sessionTimeout)`. Each element starts a new session window that can be merged with others.\n- **`mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> c)`** - Delegates to `TimeWindow.mergeWindows()` utility, which:\n  - Sorts windows by start time\n  - Identifies overlapping windows\n  - Invokes `callback.merge()` for groups that should merge\n  - Merges windows by creating a new window covering the start of the first and end of the last window in each group\n\n- **`getDefaultTrigger()`** - Returns `EventTimeTrigger.create()`\n- **`getWindowSerializer()`** - Returns `TimeWindow.Serializer`\n- **`isEventTime()`** - Returns true (windows are based on event timestamps)\n\n## 5. TimeWindow - Concrete Window Type\n**File:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/TimeWindow.java`\n\nExtends `Window` with timestamp-based windowing:\n\n- **Constructor:** `TimeWindow(long start, long end)` - Creates a window from start (inclusive) to end (exclusive)\n- **`long getStart()`, `long getEnd()`** - Query window boundaries\n- **`long maxTimestamp()`** - Returns `end - 1`, the largest timestamp in the window\n- **`boolean intersects(TimeWindow other)`, `TimeWindow cover(TimeWindow other)`** - Utility methods for merging\n- **Static `mergeWindows(Collection<TimeWindow> windows, MergeCallback<TimeWindow> c)`** - Merges overlapping time windows\n\n## 6. Window - Base Type\n**File:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/windows/Window.java`\n\nAbstract base class that all window types extend:\n\n- **`long maxTimestamp()`** - Returns the maximum timestamp still belonging to the window. Required for watermark-based window cleanup.\n\n## 7. EventTimeTrigger - Example Trigger Implementation\n**File:** `flink-runtime/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/api/windowing/triggers/EventTimeTrigger.java`\n\nDefault trigger for event-time windows (extends `Trigger<Object, TimeWindow>`):\n\n- **`onElement()`** - Registers an event-time timer at the window's max timestamp\n- **`onEventTime()`** - Fires when the timer triggers (watermark passes window end)\n- **`onProcessingTime()`** - Returns CONTINUE (processing time events are ignored)\n- **`clear()`** - Deletes the registered event-time timer\n- **`canMerge()`** - Returns true\n- **`onMerge()`** - Re-registers the event-time timer for the merged window if needed\n\n## Architecture Summary\n\nThe extension point hierarchy enables custom windowing logic:\n\n1. **WindowAssigner** determines element-to-window assignment\n2. **MergingWindowAssigner** adds window merging capability (for session windows)\n3. **Trigger** controls when aggregated window results fire\n4. **Window** types (like TimeWindow) represent the actual windows\n5. **TriggerContext** provides state management and timer infrastructure\n\nDevelopers implementing custom window assigners typically extend either `WindowAssigner` (for non-overlapping windows like tumbling windows) or `MergingWindowAssigner` (for overlapping windows like session windows). They must also provide an appropriate `Trigger` implementation via `getDefaultTrigger()`."
}

